### OS / Environment
Docker: Ubuntu 16.04

**(seems to work for musl i686/AMD64 and glibc i686)**

### Manticore version
Version: 0.1.4

### Python version
Python 2.7.12

### Dependencies
capstone==3.0.5rc2
manticore==0.1.4
ply==3.10
pyelftools==0.24
unicorn==1.0.1

### Summary of the problem
Manticore forks too many states.

### Step to reproduce the behavior
Compile the following program for AMD64 with gcc/glibc statically linked:
```C
#include <stdbool.h>
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>


int main(int argc, char * argv[], char * envv[]) {
	bool check = false;

	size_t i = 0;
	for (; envv[i] != 0; ++i) {
		if (strncmp(envv[i], "SYM=", 4) == 0) {
			check = true;
			break;
		}
	}

	if (check && strlen(envv[i]) > 4 && envv[i][4] == '7') {
		puts("Found a 7!");
	} else {
		puts("No luck today...");
		return 1;
	}
}
```

And run it:
```bash
>  gcc -g -static -o symenv symenv.c
> manticore --env SYM=+S symenv
```

### Expected behavior
Manticore terminates and creates test cases.

### Actual behavior
Manticore keeps forking new states and doesn't terminate in 5 minutes:
```
...
2017-09-06 12:19:23,737: [579] MANTICORE:INFO: load state 34
2017-09-06 12:19:26,632: [579] MANTICORE:INFO: load state 32
2017-09-06 12:19:30,020: [579] MANTICORE:INFO: load state 35
2017-09-06 12:19:40,477: [579] MANTICORE:INFO: load state 33
2017-09-06 12:19:54,689: [579] MANTICORE:INFO: load state 37
2017-09-06 12:20:07,267: [579] MANTICORE:INFO: load state 36
...
```

